ies, but also demonstrates the ways in which the artistic and political traditions of the African diaspora allow us to reinvent the Lacanian ethics of becoming.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aPsychoanalysiszUnited States. 0aRace awarenesszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRacismzUnited StatesxHistory. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Critical Theory. 4aPsychology : Psychoanalysis. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143842773740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438427737423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438427737/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles